--- !u!114 &2216422533470606458
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 380823356609093698}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 65cca2e5b07e91a45831c00644d65004, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Mb_AlmanacUI
  MainMenuController: {fileID: 0}
  HeaderImage: {fileID: 4319050544947855006}
  FlavourText: {fileID: 1741985324980071781}
  FlavourTexts:
  - 'The IUCN evaluates species using strict criteria: population size, rate of decline,
    and probability of extinction. Critically Endangered is the last tier before
    a species disappears from the wild entirely. '
  - 'The Philippines is one of only 36 biodiversity hotspots in the world, holding
    over 52,000 known species despite covering less than 0.5% of Earth''s land area.
    More than half of those species exist nowhere else on the planet. '
  - "An endemic species exists exclusively in one place \u2014 destroy its last habitat
    and it is gone from the world forever. Every animal in this Almanac is endemic
    to the Philippines. "
  - "Every forest animal holds a role others depend on \u2014 predators regulate
    prey, frugivores disperse seeds, and amphibians control insects. When one species
    disappears, its absence cascades through the entire ecosystem. "
  - "The illegal wildlife trade generates an estimated USD 23 billion annually, and
    the Philippines sits at the center of it. Rare endemic species are captured and
    sold as pets, medicine, or trophies \u2014 targeted and immediate in a way habitat
    loss is not. "
  - 'Climate change destabilizes the specific conditions species have evolved for
    over millions of years. High-altitude animals like the Mount Data Forest Frog
    face shrinking habitats as temperatures rise faster than they can adapt. '
  - "The Philippines has lost over 90% of its original forest cover since the early
    20th century. Forest-dependent species don't just lose shelter when trees fall
    \u2014 they lose their entire food chain, breeding ground, and migratory corridor
    at once. "
  - 'Chemical runoff from agriculture and industry flows into rivers, accumulating
    up the food chain through a process called bioaccumulation. Aquatic and semi-aquatic
    species like the Philippine Crocodile and Forest Turtle absorb toxins from both
    land and water. '
  - "Poachers typically target the largest, most reproductively mature individuals
    \u2014 the ones a population can least afford to lose. For slow-breeding species
    like the Philippine Eagle, which raises only one chick every two years, a single
    hunting event can set a population back by a decade. "
  - 'Roads, dams, and urban expansion fragment forests, cutting off the wildlife
    corridors animals use to find mates and food. Isolated populations become genetically
    vulnerable over generations, making them less resilient to disease and change. '
  - "Biodiversity conservation means protecting the full variety of life in an ecosystem
    \u2014 not just visible animals, but the insects, fungi, and soil microbes that
    hold everything together. Forests also provide clean water, flood regulation,
    and climate buffering that human communities depend on directly. "
  FlavorTextInterval: 5
